        "is_accepted": false,
        "last_activity_date": 1422042621,
        "creation_date": 1422042621,
        "body": "<p>To be able to kill other applications from your application has to be a \"root application\" or a system application, meaning that you get special privileges. (Without special privileges, you can only kill a process that has the same userID as the one that is doing the killing. If you are trying to kill your own process it should work.)<\/p>\n\n<p>Here is a site with details on permissions: <a href=\"http://developer.android.com/guide/topics/security/permissions.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://developer.android.com/guide/topics/security/permissions.html<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>Most third party apps do not get special privileges.<\/p>\n\n<p>If everyone were allowed to kill each other's applications, it would be chaotic.<\/p>\n\n<p>Quote:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>\" Android has no mechanism for granting permissions dynamically (at run-time) because it complicates the user experience to the detriment of security.\"<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n",
        "answer_id": 28117633,
        "question_id": 28117336
    }],
